The documents mention several film versions and adaptations of "The Victoria Cross", including a 1916 Lasky film version, a three-reel Cosmofotofilm Company film, and an extant American Silent Feature Film. The context also mentions that the story was adapted into photo-illustrated short-story adaptations in magazines such as Photoplay and Picture-Play Magazine in 1916 and 1917. This suggests that the triple is correct, and the information supports it.

mistral.reason: The context information does not indicate that the film The Victoria Cross was released in 1916. The first mention of a film adaptation was reported in June 1914, and the only extant film mentioned, according to the Library of Congress American Silent Feature Film Survival Database, was issued earlier in early 1916 but bore no resemblance to this play. Additionally, there is no evidence that any version of The Victoria Cross was completed or released during the year 1916.
